==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grab
<hw>Grab</hw> <pr>(gr⟦acr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ar. & Hind.
<ets>ghur⟦amac⟧b</ets> crow, raven, a kind of Arab ship.]</ety>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A vessel used on the Malabar coast, having two
or three masts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grab</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grab
<hw>Grab</hw> <pr>(gr⟦acr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Grabbed</conjf>
<pr>(gr⟦acr⟧bd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Grabbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Akin to Sw. <ets>grabba</ets>
to grasp. Cf. <er>Grabble</er>, <er>Grapple</er>, <er>Grasp</er>.]</ety>
<def>To gripe suddenly; to seize; to snatch; to clutch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grab</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Grab
<hw>Grab</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sudden grasp or
seizure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An instrument for clutching objects for the purpose
of raising them; -- specially applied to devices for withdrawing drills,
etc., from artesian and other wells that are drilled, bored, or
driven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Grab bag</b></col>, <cd>at fairs, a bag or box holding
small articles which are to be drawn, without being seen, on payment of
a small sum.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>Grab game</b></col>,
<cd>a theft committed by grabbing or snatching a purse or other piece of
property.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grabber</ent>⟦br⟧
